title Neth's real infrastructure — VPS cost, TigerBeetle cluster size, roadmap
prompt Keaton asked for a recommended VPN -- VPS -- cost and size optimized for Glow OS CPU compute kept separate from planned local-inference research on the Minisforum/Oculink home server, within a budget of a few hundred dollars or more per month, for a ~bandun-quality star VPS that also runs the planet, once Neth (Comlink/Ames + Mantra/Clay + Pier + ACID-compliant TigerBeetle-VSR-replicated, TAME-guided) exists -- sized to TigerBeetle's own recommended minimum consensus-node count, either under one provider/one bill or CLI-synchronized across multiple providers for outage redundancy. Asked to expand and research the prompt, run it, and report findings plus a roadmap recommendation in chat.
think Searched for ground truth rather than estimating from memory: TigerBeetle's own current docs (cluster recommendations, hardware requirements) and Urbit's own docs for what a Pier actually is, since both facts directly determine the sizing math.
think The two hard TigerBeetle facts that shape everything: exactly 6 replicas is the documented optimal cluster size, and each replica needs its OWN disk and OWN machine (both required, not recommended) -- ruling out any shortcut of running six replicas as processes on one box. Also confirmed each replica needs only 1 CPU core, which directly validates Keaton's own instinct to keep this spend separate from local-inference compute -- there was never going to be contention, since TigerBeetle doesn't use extra cores at all.
think Fetched real, current prices rather than remembered ones, and caught a real market event worth flagging: Hetzner raised cloud prices sharply on 2026-06-15, but its cost-optimized CX line (the tier this workload actually needs) rose far less than its high-performance CPX/CCX lines -- meaning the naive "just check Hetzner's homepage" instinct could easily land on the wrong, now-expensive tier if not read carefully.
think Named a real caveat rather than let the recommendation look cleaner than it is: TigerBeetle's own hardware doc specifically warns that network-attached block storage is slower and needs care for independent fault domains, so I checked which providers actually offer LOCAL NVMe (Hetzner CX, Vultr) versus which don't clearly (Contabo's SSD isn't confirmed local), and said so plainly as something to verify before committing spend, not a settled fact.
think Built three concrete plans rather than one number, because the honest answer has stages: Plan A (prove the design locally, $0, before spending anything -- the same discipline this project already lives by for every other feature); Plan B (one provider, six replicas + a shared star/planet host, ~$66.50/month); Plan C (three providers, TigerBeetle's own documented "highest availability" shape, ~$60-125/month depending on the second/third provider chosen). All three land well under the stated few-hundred-dollar ceiling, which is itself worth saying plainly rather than padding the recommendation to fill the budget.
think Researched real multi-provider Terraform practice rather than inventing a synchronization scheme -- confirmed the current best practice is per-provider isolated state (never combine two clouds in one state file), found a live, current public example (abaasi256/vps-infra-recovery) doing exactly this shape across AWS/Hetzner/Contabo, and pointed to it directly per this project's own "grow from what already works" instinct rather than design from nothing.
obs The single most valuable finding is the negative one: there was never a real tension between VPS spend and local-inference compute to resolve, because TigerBeetle's own single-core-per-replica design means the two budgets don't compete by construction. Naming that plainly was more useful than any dollar figure.
file external-research/20260714-012125_neth-vps-cost-and-cluster-plan.md why: the full cost/cluster research -- Pier facts, TigerBeetle hardware facts, real current pricing across four providers, three concrete plans, the roadmap recommendation
file expanding-prompts/20260714-012125_neth-vps-cost-expanded.md why: the research-grounded expanded form of the seed
file active-reviving/README.md why: Neth's revival entry now links the real cost plan alongside the earlier architecture design
recommend check-in -- no infrastructure was provisioned; the recommendation is Plan A (the $0 local witness) first, and this document is ready for Keaton's word on Plan B or C whenever the design is proven.
